# Muncherz — Environment Variables
# Copy this file to .env.local and fill in actual values
# NEVER commit .env.local — it is in .gitignore

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# SUPABASE
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=
SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=
# ⛔ SERVER ONLY — never expose to client

# Auth is handled entirely by Supabase Auth (Phone OTP, Email+Password,
# Email+TOTP) — see ARCHITECTURE.md "Security Architecture". This stack
# does not use NextAuth.js anywhere, so there are no NEXTAUTH_* variables
# here. If you find NEXTAUTH_SECRET/NEXTAUTH_URL referenced in older
# branches or copied boilerplate, remove it — it's dead config from a
# different auth library and was incorrectly left in earlier drafts of
# this file.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# PAYMENTS — PAYMOB
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
PAYMOB_API_KEY=
# ⛔ SERVER ONLY
PAYMOB_INTEGRATION_ID_CARD=
PAYMOB_INTEGRATION_ID_JAZZCASH=
PAYMOB_INTEGRATION_ID_EASYPAISA=
PAYMOB_HMAC_SECRET=
# ⛔ SERVER ONLY — used to verify webhook signatures
PAYMOB_WEBHOOK_URL=

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# SMS / OTP PROVIDER
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
SMS_PROVIDER_API_KEY=
# ⛔ SERVER ONLY
SMS_PROVIDER_SENDER_ID=

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# KITCHEN LCD SECURITY
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
KITCHEN_PIN_SALT=
# ⛔ SERVER ONLY — a fixed app-wide secret value mixed into every PIN
# hash. This is technically a PEPPER, not a salt: bcrypt/argon2 already
# generate a unique random salt per hash automatically. Keep this var,
# but don't assume it's redundant with bcrypt's built-in salting — it
# isn't, it serves a different purpose (a secret an attacker with just
# the DB dump still wouldn't have).

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# DEVELOPER PANEL — 2FA
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# ⚠️ Do NOT use a single global TOTP secret here for "all developers."
# Each developer/admin needs their OWN enrolled TOTP factor — use
# Supabase Auth's native MFA enrollment (per-user, stored in the DB)
# instead of a single shared app-level secret. A shared secret means
# anyone holding it can authenticate as any developer, with no way to
# revoke one person without rotating it for the whole team. See
# SECURITY.md "Authentication & Session Security" for the full
# explanation. If this project genuinely has exactly one developer for
# the life of the MVP, document that explicitly here rather than
# leaving it ambiguous.
DEVELOPER_2FA_SECRET=
# ⛔ SERVER ONLY — see warning above before using this as written

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# MONITORING
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
NEXT_PUBLIC_SENTRY_DSN=
SENTRY_AUTH_TOKEN=
# ⛔ SERVER ONLY — production only

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# MAPS / DELIVERY VALIDATION
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY=

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# APP CONFIG
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_NAME=Muncherz
NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL=
NODE_ENV=development

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
# CHANGES MADE (AUDIT PASS)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
# - Removed NEXTAUTH_SECRET and NEXTAUTH_URL. This stack uses Supabase
#   Auth exclusively (per every other doc in this set) — NextAuth.js is
#   never mentioned anywhere else. These were dead, mismatched config
#   left over from a different auth library, sitting in the one file
#   most likely to get blindly copied into .env.local without question.
# - Clarified KITCHEN_PIN_SALT is functioning as a pepper, not a salt,
#   so it doesn't get "cleaned up" as redundant by someone who knows
#   bcrypt already salts automatically.
# - Flagged DEVELOPER_2FA_SECRET as written: a single global secret
#   implies one shared TOTP code for every developer account, which
#   breaks per-user revocation and accountability. Recommended Supabase
#   Auth's native per-user MFA enrollment instead. Did not remove the
#   variable outright since the team may genuinely be single-developer
#   right now — but it should be a deliberate choice, not an oversight.
